What qualitities help you to have a good relationship others
I believe that showing genuine care and being open-minded in conversations are essential for building strong relationships. When you make an effort to understand another person's perspective, it helps minimize unncesary conflict and shows respect.
It also creates a more constructive environment where both sides can communicate effectively and work toward a common goal. In addition, having strong emotional intelligence is very important, as it helps resolve misunderstandings before they escalate into serious conflicts.

Do you often have problems with family members
Not very often, but minor disagreements do come up from time to time, which I think is completely normal in close-knit families. We usually address any issues through open and honest conversations.
By doing so, we can better understand each other's perspectives and prevent misunderstandings from escalating into serious conflicts. In addition, I believe mutual respect plays a key role in maintaining healthy long-term relationships.

Do you think conflicts among family members are unavoidable
Yes, definitely. When people live under the same roof, minor disagreements are almost inevitable. However, I believe that conflict can be healthy if they're handled properly.
It can act as a catalyst for stronger relationships by helping people understand each other's perspectives, identify the root causes of issues, and work together toward solutions.
In fact, this process can strengthen family bonds over time. What matters most is maintaining open and constructive communication to prevent misunderstandings from building up.

What behavior of others hurts you most
I find passive-aggressive behaviour particularly hurtful, as it can have a detrimental effect on relationships. Working with someone who creates ambibuity instead of communicating clearly can be quite frustrating.
I would much prefer people to be upfront rather than conceal their concerns or resentment, because that kind of behavior undermines trust, amplifies issues, and makes them harder to resolve.

When you have upset someone with your actions, what do you try to do
Whenever I realize that I've upset someone, I make it a priority to offer a sincere apology. I strongly believe taking accountability helps defuse tension and paves the way for reconciliation.
I also take time to reflect on my behavior so that I can learn from the situation and avoid repeating the same mistake in the future.

Describe a disagreement that you had with another person
- what it was about
- who you had this disagreement with
- how you resolved it
- and explain what happened after the disagreement

One disagreement that stands out happened about a year ago with a close friend of mine. We were planning a weekend getaway to the mountains and were both really excited about it.

The issue came up when we discussed how to split the costs. I felt we should divide everything equally, while my friend preferred to pay more since he had chosen a more expensive cabin that I hadn’t fully agreed to. What started as a minor disagreement quickly escalated, partly because we were both quite stressed from work and neither of us wanted to compromise at first.

Eventually, I realized it wasn’t worth risking our friendship over money. I suggested that we sit down, go through all the expenses, and find a fair solution. In the end, he agreed to cover the extra cost of the cabin, and I offered to pay for some activities during the trip to balance things out.

After resolving the issue, we both felt a bit embarrassed about how heated things had become, but we were able to laugh it off. In fact, the trip turned out to be even more enjoyable because we had cleared the air beforehand.

This experience taught me the importance of open communication and addressing issues early before they escalate. Since then, we’ve both made an effort to discuss plans more clearly in advance, which has strengthened our friendship.
